Fixing specs so they actually test our functionality

Because Loquacious::Undefined objects have no methods defined on them, all
the RSpec "should" methods get consumed when applied to udnefiend return
values. Any spec assert will be true because the assertion never happens.

We change this style ...

  cfg.one.two.should be == 'foo'

into this style ...

  cfg.one.two.eql?('foo').should be_true

and all is better. This caught a few bugs in the loquacious system with
respect to merging configurations.

Only create one Iterator when converting to a hash.

Creating multiple iterators when converting to a hash is inefficient. Nested
configuration objects will be iterated multiple times. This changes creates
only one iterator and uses sneaky parent namespacing to keep track of the
nesting depth.

Removing unreachable code paths.

Undefined objects will never be returned by the Iterator. We can safely remove
checks in the Node struct for Undefined values.

The Iterator class now skips Undefined objects in the Configuration.

Undefined objects end up in the Configuration when an attempt is make to
access a value that does not exist. These are used to print error messages to
the screen saying "hey, that does not exist". Unfortuantely the Undefined
objects were also showing up in help messages via the iterator.

This patch causes the iterator to ignore these Undefined objects when it finds
them.

Add #to_hash to Configuration

This will recursively convert a Configuration object to a hash. This allows us
to merge the hash with an option hash or pass it into a method which accepts an
option hash.
